name: Ralph Benton Wilson Iv
message: whoa. thanks DAN!NEWlINEbefore i go ahead with "correcting" the measure, i think there are a few considerations. NEWlINEdividing likes or comments by measures is nice because it is normalized (a measure between 0 and 1), and sort of adjusts for the inflation phenomena but it also sort of assumes a linear relationship between group size and liking/commenting. i don't think this is the case. i think it might bias the other way toward popular early posts (which is fun, and worth looking at).NEWlINEother options might be dividing by number of active posters during that week/month. this is fun because a value greater than one means that a post drew a bunch of lurkers out of the woodwork.NEWlINElurkers in the woodworkNEWlINEthe joined-date data is interesting in itself. hopefully we can have a nice graphic soon of the explosion, then that awkward moment where some Demosthenes and Locke shut it off (myself among the conspirators).NEWlINE(hunh, it occurs to me, now that we have access to all the data outside of facebook, we really do have the option of becoming an open group if anyone really really wanted to, or we needed to to save a life or something. all we'd have to do is start another group and leave it open.)

message: also i thought it might still skew towards later posts, because as activity increased it would be more prevalent in people's newsfeeds, creating kind of an activity feedback loop. i guess we can do some investigating tho

message: True enough.  Some people only show their place of work, which would take more time to google and find the corresponding ZIP.  I did it a few times, and it took me around 45 seconds to google+discover+enter the data in a spreadsheet.  As the FSU people can all be dumped into the same city rapidly, and there are probably 500 Tallahasseans on here, I think it's probably a solid 10 hours worth of manual entry for everyone else.  NEWlINENEWlINENow, at the industry standard for data entry, y'all would owe me around $140, but this is important stuff, so $200 is more like it.  I accept Dogecoin and vegan baked goods as alternative forms of payment.  You have one day to accept or submit a counteroffer. message: I for one would like to congratulate everyone on the stupid amount of dedication we've had to this page. Some of these jokes are so inside and so off the cuff that the appropriate response often lies somewhere between ignoring them and reposting them over and over until all our other friends delete us. message: the day my internet was out, i did actually come up with a rubric to measure certain quality/qualities of band names. yet, i personally believe that unleashing such a metric on our current civilization may have catastrophic effects. also, in order to really test it out, i would need to implement it across the collection of all submissions, and check the correlation with likes/engageability. a quirk that one would have to consider in any analysis of "quality" is the bizarre dichotomy between bandnames that get a lot of likes, and bandnames that start really long or creative threads. they are not the same. (i actually do hope to do this when i finish my dissertation this year.)NEWlINENEWlINE i will say that given the nature of the group, one should a series of "septembers" as the group reaches new networks, and as these networks settle into the use of the group. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eternal_SeptemberNEWlINE(totally coincidental to Jimmy's random pick of "september 1975", i think)NEWlINENEWlINE the reposts will come forever, because our culture has finitely many symbols to use for recombination. either we let reposts and silly names bring us joy, or they will turn us into crotchety old persons. . .

name: Nelson Trautman
message: these are my BSG themed band name suggestions

name: Dale Bridges
message: I disagree. While the final season felt a little rushed, I think they managed to wrap things up sufficiently. They had to end it eventually.

name: Dale Bridges
message: And bad writing? C'mon, you can accuse BSG of many things, but bad writing isn't one of them.

name: Nelson Trautman
message: And there were a million good ways to end it, which they failed to come up with. The last season made it painfully clear that they had no plan and there was no actual mystery to be discovered by the viewer. Instead, the lazy writers were just making things up as they went along, with no clue as to what the actual resolution would be. The decision to retcon in the "FINAL FOUR CYLONS" storyline is insulting to the viewer. It basically became a different show with a completely different backstory that was never part of the plot or drama before season 4.

name: Nelson Trautman
message: The final plot resolution is "God did it." That is literally deus ex machina. It is bad writing.

name: Dale Bridges
message: Actually, the entire series was building toward that. I honestly don't see how they could have ended it any other way. You just wanted things explained in a neat little package and you didn't get it. I like the fact that it was more open ended.

name: Nelson Trautman
message: lol, I did NOT want anything explained in a neat little package, and that is not at all my criticism

name: Nelson Trautman
message: and the entire series was not building toward that. The entire last season is such a forced piece of garbage that disregards everything that happened before it.

name: Nelson Trautman
message: Dramatic tension comes from when two characters are on an unstoppable collision course and they meet in a conflict which is decided by their strengths, weaknesses and circumstances. They conflict because it could not have been otherwise.NEWlINENEWlINEBad writing is when all the sudden Lee is mad at his dad for no reason or Starbuck starts to act like a psycho JUST to affect some shallow plotline where the writers decided they wanted to see these two characters fight.

name: Nelson Trautman
message: the show is full of forgivable problems like the above as long as the overall plot is interesting, which it was until they left new caprica

name: Nelson Trautman
message: then everything became completely disposable and weightless because you knew that it was just whatever the writers were feeling like today, and that all of the hints to the mystery that were dropped previously actually had no bearing on the final outcome and you wasted your time if you tried to figure out what was going on.

name: Nelson Trautman
message: My criticism is actually the exact opposite of what you think it is. The "God did it" ending ties things up TOO neatly. It's cheap.
